Thanks for the extra info Gerald. It looks like Safari on iPhone cannot handle the 204 HTTP status code. You could try disabling the PHP which returns the 204 code: open "mod/hotpot/attempt.php" with your favorite text editor locate the following lines (around line 153) 
```text
// continue without reloading the page


header("Status: 204");


header("HTTP/1.0 204 No Response");
```
 comment out the header lines, thus: 
```text
// continue without reloading the page


// header("Status: 204");


// header("HTTP/1.0 204 No Response");
```
 save the modified file Please try that and see if it helps in the Safari case. If it does then you can make the code a little cleverer to check to see if the browser is Safari. If it isn't iPhone Safari, send the 204 status code as usual. If it is iPhone Safari, don't do anything. You could also try just commenting out the "header" first line, and see if that helps. regards Gordon

